segments.text: trying to develop this system.
Who was the director of the?
Hood Gibson, G.D. Gibson, and J.D.
Pruitt was the associate director.
He was the one that came to Matagorda County and talked to me about my interest in coming up here.
I said, what does the future hold after that?
Well, the future, you know, he planted the idea that, I guess I'd been spotted in terms of, you know, the work I've done with my master and so forth.
He, um,
suggested that maybe after that there might be a possibility for further graduate study that they see if they could find help for me.
Compare the, these are the only salary numbers I'm going to ask, what was your, what was your, your...
I remember my first salary, $2,650.
That was here?
No, at the county.
At the county.
And I guess I was, when I left Matagorda County, I was probably in the mid $3,000, $3,500, $3,800 in there, and I think when I came up here,
I can't remember without referring, but it wasn't a lot more than that.
And this is what year?
And you had to furnish a car.
Now you've got some expenses for a car, usually a flat mile, but your county agent wore a car out almost every year.
I mean, in fact, for a while there, I did have to buy a car almost every year because it went on so many miles.
And when you got here, where were the offices?
Well, they are now in the system building.
Well...
About that time, well, they had just moved.
There used to be what's now the Trigon.
The whole building was an extension building.
And about the time when I came up here, they had located their headquarters offices in the system building on the north side of the system building, where they still are.
And the specialists that had been all in one building together were then housed with the departments, the agronomists, the animal scientists, and so forth.
So it was basically the administrative staff plus the bookkeeping and all of that.
Well, they had more of that building.
They had the second floor, too, the offices over there.
And Director Gibson reported to whom, as far as you know?
Well, there were several reorganizations, and through the years there was always a change.
I think at that time he reported to the president of the system.
I guess at that time, I don't know when the system organization came in.
It comes and goes.
It comes and goes.
But I think basically he reported to Gilchrist, I guess.
And where did you and your wife find a place to live?
Over in South College Station.
And we just rented because we had this notion that
probably would be going off to further graduate study after that.

And after finishing or doing pretty much all of this number crunching, and we didn't have all the fancy computers in those days, had to do everything with a calculator, we used the Gilmer-Akin thing as a model of trying to, what we came up with was we had a measure of what we thought the counties deserved in terms of a staff,
and then a way to break down the finances.

As I said, if a county had a lot of resources, they were expected to pay more and more for each particular agent because, I don't know if you're aware of this, agents always receive a part of their salary directly from the county.
That's right.

And usually the expenses, office, secretaries were furnished by the counties, and the agents were drawing anywhere from $20 to $30, $40, $50, depending on the situation, some of them much more than that, from the county.
You'd get a separate check.
You'd get a check from A&M and
They took all the deductions out of here in terms of retirement programs and insurance and everything.
And the county didn't do any of that.
And so you had two checks that you got paid for.
Anyway, after I had, and I worked in the administrative building over there because I had to have constant access to the administrative staff.
And we often met with them to, you know,
explore ideas and ways to do it, and then I'd have to do more number crunching, and they wanted this, and it didn't look right, so I'd do more number crunching.
Anyway, I went through a lot of this, and then I also, during that period, was that afterwards?
No, I guess that was later.
Anyway, I came here in 55, and along about that time,
They organized this National Extension Center for Advanced Study at University of Wisconsin, financed by Kellogg.
And they gave fellowships, which means you didn't have to work.
And it was considered a very generous fellowship if you could qualify.
Well, I had a choice of going to
There was another program that several administrators participated in was the public administration program at Harvard.
But you'd get a doctorate of public administration, which, although it would have been nice to go to Harvard and have that in your record, I thought a PhD was probably better from anywhere else.
And Wisconsin was fairly respectable as far as the graduate school is concerned.
Anyway, Kellogg provided a grant for five years of getting
Oh, a couple of dozen or so young people or mid-career people identified that might have other administrative potential.
And it was a competitive thing.
You applied, and if you got it, you got a, at that time, I think it was $4,800 a year tax-free income.
And so in 1957, we took off.
And as I think I mentioned to you before, I anticipated these moves.
I finished the program in 18 months, if you can believe this, because I could study full time, and I also had, at that time they still required the two languages.

I had done all of my homework on the languages and passed my exams on the languages very early, whereas most of my colleagues in the program were spending more time on the languages than they were on the courses.
So I took a full load, got my languages out of the way, and then as far as my thesis study,
further elaboration of this measuring county workload and financing thing and developed into a 350-page thesis.
Now, did you take leave?
I was given leave.
Given leave without pay.
But still.
With no assurance that I'd get that particular job, but they said, you will have a job when you come back.
And in fact, Hutchison was director by then.
He wanted me to come back early.
He kept pressuring.
They had some assignments for me that they wanted me to do.
And I had some other offers when I left there, but he arranged to offer me the assistant director position for some special activity areas.
And that made me a member of the administrative staff.
I guess I was only, what, 30, 31 years old by then.
But I became a part of the administration at that time.
I guess when I was administrative assistant, I really wasn't officially a part.
But he had me come back as assistant director.
And that's 1957?
No, that would be 59.
I went to school in 57.
57, came back in 59, and I think I became assistant director.
I'm coming into the rudder years now, I guess.
That's the same year I got here.
I came back here in 59, in the spring of 59, and was involved in several special projects.
Describe, as you came as assistant director, describe the Extension Service and its leadership.
What was its organization?
Well, John Hutchison was director by then, and he was an outstanding director.
And I enjoyed serving with him.
He was director, I guess, 19 years.
And J.D.
Pruitt was associate director.

They made a good combination, Mr. Pruitt was not a what you call a gregarious person to deal with and I had of course going through administrative training programs I had always felt that an organization would work effectively if you could have
what I call the Mr. Outside and Mr.
Inside.
And the outside man had to be the head man because most of the time people don't want to deal with the number two or three person.
And I saw that operate.
Hutchison was very effective working with the legislature, with the leadership in the state.
Mr. Pruitt did the work back home in terms of all the staffing and budgets and personnel problems and all of that.
I guess the administrative staff at that time was about eight or nine people.
You had a state program leader for agriculture, one in home economics, 4-H, communications, fiscal, personnel, all of those types of things.
And it was a good learning experience to work that closely to administration.
Had the black and white agents yet been integrated?
That came, I guess,
In the 60s.
That involved me very heavily.
Oh, okay.
We had to go through a lot of the things at that time with that program.
And also I got a lot of special assignments.
Kellogg at that time had financed another program called the National Agriculture Communications Project, centered at Iowa State University, in which they trained

two or three people in each state intensively, and it was kind of the in-thing then of principles of communication, organizations function better, people could communicate better, and you could reach audiences better.

There was a lot of this was based on Bowen and Beale's sociology work at Iowa State where they learned how the process of how new ideas are accepted, they call it the fusion process, of when people first hear about a new idea.
how they go about the mental processes they go through, and finally accepting a new variety of corn or a new way of doing things or something.
We were given training.
Three of us were selected to participate in an intensive three-week program at the University of Wyoming.

And then we came back, and we had to train everybody in the staff, all 1,100, 1,200 people that were on the staff about that time in district meetings, different kinds of state meetings, two or three day, I guess, meetings where we gave everybody this type of training.
interpersonal relations and communications and how you get ideas across to people and get them to accept them and all this type of thing.
That was a very exciting project.
As I said, I was involved in special things.

Back in the county, I had already gotten extremely frustrated with the lack of any guidance in terms of how files were kept in the counties because the county agents had to depository of all kinds of information.
And you had a real problem.
Every county agent set up their own system, and no two people think.
And I guess part of that was my library experience.
I knew that you could organize things.
And so I started out in the county of trying.
At that time, I had worked in the library here.
I had to do a decimal system.
I thought, well, why can't you use the same principles, maybe in organizing office files?
But I found out that that was a little too complicated for the average agent.
So I started on my own in the county of developing a sort of a filing system.

And my contention was that if there was a similar filing system in every county, that when agents went from one county to the other, they would either face one problem of learning the other guy's or his predecessor's system, which probably was incomprehensible, or set up his own, which was a very huge process because in most counties you had
five or six, ten file cabinets full of information.
I mean, you had to have, you know, somebody come in, what's the formula for a whitewashing offense?
I mean, you don't remember these things, you have to have a place to find this information.
And so I, so it had been tried before three or three times in Texas and always bogged down.
It had been tried in other states, it had been tried nationally, and I said, I think I can do it.
And I was given full
time off and resources to do it, and I developed this system in about a year's time, but I involved everybody in the staff, every specialist.
We set up the sections by disciplines, animal science, but we did it as an agent would look at it.
You know, he wouldn't look at it in terms of, you know, breeding and so forth, but he would look at it from the way he does it.
So we set up a rather elaborate filing system, and we went
We trained, gave people, everybody in the state, a full day training program on it, and even provided the materials of the dividers, the guidance, and so forth.
So that was a very, I thought it was a thing that made a great contribution to the organization.
And as far as I know, the system is still being utilized.
So I was kind of jumping from projects to projects.
And gradually, I was beginning.
what I'd call more real administrative responsibilities.
When you started out, did you replace anybody?
No, no, I think it was more of a new slot for special projects, I guess you'd call it.
But gradually I was given responsibility over units of other people, like in that period of time, community development became a big

new thrust from the Lyndon Johnson, you know, working with low-income farmers and so forth, and I started giving leadership to some of those kind of programs, or had the people that were employed in those areas, and got involved in, I was always available for special things, the Century Study, I got stuck in that.
That was in the 60s.
Mr. Rutter was, early on, was president of both the campus and the system.
So Dr. Hutchinson, no, Hutchinson, isn't it?
Hutchinson.
H-U-T-C-H-I-S-O-N?
Hutchinson, yeah.
All right.
He reported to President Rutter that,
the what was Mr.
Rudder's what was their working relationship and how do you think he felt about the extension service Rudder?
Did they did they work well together?
I think so I mean I think so Mr.

Rudder had a good understanding of rural agricultural I mean he had that background himself I think he recognized the important role that the extension service played particularly in the 90 percent of the counties in

of thing, and I think he recognized, which I always say, land grant, I have made the statement at land grant meetings that, you know, you get a lot of people that come out of non-land grant situations that get into leadership positions, and I always say that presidents of non-land grant universities would give their right arm to have what a land grant university president has with this outreach into every single community.
I think a lot of
presidents that don't have that appreciation don't realize what they have with the extension service.
And I think Mr.
Rudder understood that, and I think he used the extension service for... Can you think of any examples where he demonstrated how well he could relate to agricultural people?
Mr.
Rudder?
Yeah, places where he used to... Well, he was always at home in agricultural circles.
I mean, he had no problem... Well, I guess he was at home in all kinds of circles, but
You know, he did grow up in a rural area and understood farmers and farmers' problems.
I don't think he was a farmer himself, was he?
I think they had...
They had a ranch.
They did have a ranch, but they had business that served farmers.
Yeah, yeah.
But he had a good understanding of, I think, farm problems and I think supported the Extension Service very well, and as far as I know,
at least from my vantage point, there were no problems in terms of relationships and so forth.
Would you agree with me?
I think that he felt more relaxed and comfortable in front of an agricultural group than he did in front of a faculty group.
Yeah, I'd say that's probably a fair assessment.
There was a lot of, I guess, unhappiness that I detected during the century study and so forth, particularly from people who
At about that time, I would guess in engineering and agriculture that 80% of the faculty were A&M graduates themselves.
Of course, then the decision was made to try to get more outside, which was necessary if the school was going to grow.
But I think there was a lot of resentment on the pure academics that he had no academic credentials as such.
Now, as far as I remember, the Century Study is 62-3-4, and you were appointed to the committee, weren't you?
They had four task forces.
I worked with one of the task forces.
That's what I thought.
The chairman I worked with was Harry Moore, and they had 25.
Describe what you can remember of that task force's work.
Describe what that task force did.
Well, it was a very interesting experience.
I mean, these were the very top people in Texas, political, industrial, business, agricultural, you name it, top leaders, men and women.
all parts of the state.
It was interesting to see how they interacted and became a group and made their recommendation.
I think each task force has sort of an area to look at.
And the staff person was kind of the go-for.
You know, made arrangements for the meetings and got the resource people they needed, kept
notes of the meeting and wrote up their materials, which were turned into your group, I guess, and processed them somehow.
I don't remember all the details, but it was an interesting experience.
Do you think that was an important activity in terms of its long-range results?
It was absolutely essential.
A&M would not have been anywhere from my viewpoint where they are today, because the report dealt with the basic issues about co-education, mandatory core thing,
name change, all of those things, as I think we indicated before.
My own conclusion is nobody could have done this other than Earl Rudder, because he did have a non-academic background, but he knew that he had to have the state leadership.
If the state leadership made these recommendations, that they would be more acceptable, and I think it turned out that way.
Do you remember any opinions Dr. Hutchinson had about some of those basic changes?
Well, he didn't, I mean, he didn't, deliberately didn't try to influence me.
I was just pretty much, I guess that was almost a full-time assignment those days.
Almost.
I mean, I didn't.
Like, I never heard of his being for or against.
No, I think he was a true blue Aggie, and I think he had to, but he was also progressive.
He'd gone to the University of Chicago and got his Ph.D.
I mean, I think he recognized that some of the change, but he tended to be, you know, conservative, uh,
I know he had a real problem, and I told my wife the other day, I think if it hadn't been for me, he would have got himself in trouble.
He was a hard time accepting women wearing pants.
Really?
Describe that, because that's good history.
Well, there was a period there when women started wearing what are called pantsuits, something like that, and he was just adamantly against it.
He just thought it was not professionally appropriate, and I
I guess I was a little of the younger generation, and I told him, don't waste your shots on it.
It's a fashion thing.
It's probably come and go.
But he had a real hard time accepting it.
You see, if you go back far enough in time, I mean, that generation, it was like school teaching.
A woman couldn't teach if she was married, for example, or divorced or something like that.
It was a different area.
I think he had also...
more conservative viewpoints about the racial thing.
I mean, I'm sure that he felt the way the system had arranged it, and I think it was from a sincere basis that he felt the black community was better served with having their own professionals.
They could relate to each other, and there's some evidence that's true.
I mean, even now they try to identify people.
There was one other thing I got very involved in that I'm very proud of that's, I guess,
made my reputation a little more national is that I participated with the federal office.
They had a small research unit at the Department of Agriculture in Washington, only a handful of people.
But in the war and poverty time days, some monies became available for extra studies.
We were very concerned that we, with our home economics program, particularly in nutrition, that we weren't
you know, really reaching people effectively, the poorest of the poor.

And this is very unusual for Extension to get involved that deeply, but there was a lady who was a research expert out of Washington, and if you look at my resume, that's identified on there as a publication that Dr. Starley Hunter and I did a long-term project
In the Hispanic area of El Paso, what was unusual about it, in this type of a thing, we actually had a control group.
It's called Reaching Mexican-American Families.
We actually had about an area of 700, 800 families, another area that demographically, statistically,
was similar.
We didn't do any work with this group, but we worked with the other group.

And well, to make a long story short, we found out that we could utilize what we call paraprofessionals, people out of that community, homemakers, mothers, bring them in and employ them at minimum wage, give them intensive training in nutrition, human nutrition, and let them go back out in the communities and
that they could get access to the homes where a professional could not.
And we found that, and it was a seven-year project, we found that using this technique was an effective way of reaching this audience.
They actually improved in their knowledge of nutrition and made some changes in their practices

We had identified one of the problems was that as much of the population was in a migratory status that had come from Mexico, what we found particularly with the succeeding generations is that they brought the best of both cultures and pick up the worst, I mean fast food, potato chip, protein.
If you analyze their own diets the way they were in the traditional days, they were probably pretty good in terms of the beans.
And anyway, we identified that this could be done with low-income audiences.
And this gave rise to a program, I don't know if you've heard about, you probably did if you were president, of the Expanded Food and Nutrition Educational Program, which was financed in the Johnson
war and poverty days.
I guess it even started out, I guess, even the Kennedy times, but money started becoming available.
And the Department of Agriculture was given special monies by Congress to carry out a nationwide program of reaching the poorest of the poor with a nutrition program.
And it was based on the results.
And that program continues to this day, although it has not been funded.
Its funding has diminished.
We, the basic unit in Texas, every state was given the money but could operate the program.
But it was based on the principles that we had identified of employing paraprofessionals, giving them intensive training, even though they may have only had little or no formal education themselves.
But they were given very simple materials, recipes to get into the homes and try to get families to.
There was no money given.

It also, but these people were given information about when they found problems, they went house to house, or what they were encouraged to do is to get two or three or four of their neighbors together and talk about these things.
But they were also given information about the other social services that were available for families, food stamps later on and all this type of thing.
And a lot of these people were unaware, a lot of these people were
totally afraid of government or anything.
These people were not even identified as government.
They were just neighbors helping you.
And I think it was a successful program.
And as I said, I think it's, as I said, this research that we participated in, it was a difficult thing to do because you had to train people to do it.
You had to get detailed information about what they, when we started the project, we went into the experimental area and actually found out the base of knowledge.
people had about nutrition.
Then we conducted the program and measured it two years later, and then again seven years later as to the actual changes.
Did the same thing with the control group.
It was an interesting project, but as I said, it was one of the bases used for this national program that Congress funded and still continues to fund.
In fact, that program, I was, the basic unit in Texas, which I was given sort of, even though it was a home economics area, it was given the
responsibility of the training, the intellectual support of the training materials and so forth.
The home economics staff, of course, the nutritionists were involved in the nutrition training of it.
And what we did, we set up only in urban areas and a few rural areas what we call an expanded foods and nutrition unit, which included 30 paraprofessionals.
which was too money for one professional to supervise.
So we had an intermediate group called program aides, who were also people of that community.
But they worked full time, were paid full time.
And one professional.
So a unit consisted of 30 people, mostly women in most cases, homemakers themselves, who were employed.
to reach out to their neighbors and friends on this program.
You had a program aide who supervised 10 of those.
You had to schedule things pretty carefully.
You do this block and this type of thing.
They were trained every week, given a half a day of training every week.
And then you had one professional nutritionist who supervised the whole program.
This led to, talking about the growth of bureaucracy, I once was at a land grant meeting.

some Californian you know they have the huge counties out there bragging about the size of their staffs and I said well I can I think I can top your story I said we have one county where we have over 100 employees he was absolutely staggered and it became I could actually in San Antonio we set up there's only city we set up two units if you're familiar with San Antonio they have both the
So that was 34 times two.
And then we got a Sears funding project for doing work with low-income youth, a 4-H program.
And they hired part-time paraprofessionals, about 30 or 40 of those.
So you add all those together, not even counting the professional staff at one time.
We had over 100 people working in one county alone.
But this was mostly either federal money or
trying to reach low-income families.
We need to quit, because you go to 10 o'clock.
Aren't we about through?
